        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-03-03T18:51:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-03-03T18:51:00-05:00" n="422"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d422">
                <head>422. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Pakistan</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d422fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1967–69,
                            <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> (US) 15–8 <gloss target="#t_Pak1"
                            >PAK</gloss>. Confidential. Drafted by Guy C. Mallett (<gloss
                            target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_PAF1">PAF</gloss>);
                        cleared by Horbaly (<gloss target="#t_USDA1">USDA</gloss>/FAS), and Palmer
                            (<gloss target="#t_AIDNESA1">AID/NESA</gloss>); and approved by
                            <persName corresp="#p_SJW1">Spain</persName>. Repeated to Lahore and the
                        Embassy Office in Karachi.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-03-03T18:51:00-05:00">March 3, 1967, 6:51 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>148588. 1. Deputy Chairman Planning Commission MM Ahmad accompanied by Ambassador
                        <persName corresp="#p_HA1">Hilaly</persName> met with Agriculture Under
                    Secretary <persName corresp="#p_SJA2">Schnittker</persName> and Assistant
                    Secretary Jacobson March 2 with requests for 250,000 tons wheat for <gloss
                        target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> ’67 (<persName corresp="#p_HA1"
                    >Hilaly</persName>) and 1.5 million tons for <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss>
                    ’68 (Ahmad) with deliveries of latter to commence in June.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d422fn2">During his visit to Washington Ahmad pressed his request
                        for food assistance for Pakistan in meetings with <persName
                            corresp="#p_REV1">Eugene Rostow</persName> on March 6, with <persName
                            corresp="#p_WWH1">Wriggins</persName> on March 6, and with Jacobson on
                        March 10. (Ahmad’s meetings with Rostow and Jacobson were reported in
                        telegrams 150823 and 153129 to Rawalpindi, March 8 and 10 respectively;
                        ibid.; his meeting with <persName corresp="#p_WWH1">Wriggins</persName> was
                        summarized in a March 6 memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_WWH1"
                            >Wriggins</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">Walt
                            Rostow</persName>; <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName>
                        Library, National Security File, Country File, Pakistan, Vol. VII, Memos,
                        10/66–7/67)</note>
                </p>
                <p>2. <persName corresp="#p_SJA2">Schnittker</persName> agreed to look into both
                    requests. In regard to <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> ’68 request and timing
                    of these deliveries <persName corresp="#p_SJA2">Schnittker</persName> said, in
                    the context of U.S. supply situation and forthcoming consideration of global
                    requests, that “we’ll do our best on the timing.”</p>
                <p>3. Ahmad’s presentation of food situation followed same lines as earlier talk
                    with <persName corresp="#p_GWS1">Gaud</persName> (reported separately) and he
                    provided same Aide-mémoire.<note n="3" xml:id="d422fn3">Not found.</note> He
                    stressed two additional points (1) <gloss target="#t_GOP1">GOP</gloss> approval
                    of policies and resources for agricultural production which would enable <gloss
                        target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 1970 to be last year of concessional wheat
                    imports, and (2) provisional decision to shift to local currency convertible
                    payment as follows: <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> ’68 one-third, <gloss
                        target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> ’69 one-half, <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss>
                    ’70 three-fourths.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
